utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: All those kids --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You know these kids, these kids are rotten.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Well, their Tiananmen Square -- I don't know, Juan. What do you think? I mean, speaking of Tiananmen Square. China is -- I think pollutes more than the E.U. and America combined.

utterances.speaker: DAGEN MCDOWELL, HOST
utterances.utterance: Thank you. CO2 emissions in the United States are back to where they were in the mid-1980's. This is just balderdash. Why aren't they protesting in the countries where it really matters that they reduce emissions? I don't have a problem with kids going out like, what was I doing if I skipped school one day? I would be dipping Skoal and going --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Dipping Skoal.

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.utterance: Go to see Eraserhead. That's not the problem. The problem is these Democratic presidential candidates are basically preaching something that is dangerous and immoral. They want to reduce -- they want to destroy our quality of life and reduce how we live in this nation. It doesn't make any sense. And I just want to -- speaking young people to old people. I want to call out Mick Jagger --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.utterance: -- on Instagram. He posted this earlier. I need to stand in support of the global climate strike today. We need to do everything we can to protect our planet and humanity. He has done -- he has the biggest carbon footprint of anybody walking on the face of planet earth right now. He has 8 kids. He's still procreating --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: All right, all right. We got your point. We got your point. But let me just say something, so straws are going to impact your quality of life, Dagen? How about seatbelts?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: She didn't even believed what she was saying when she talked about straws. You know who I'm talking --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Harris.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Let me get this straight. So seatbelts, when the government says -- is it a nanny state to say wear a seatbelt or only go 65?

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.utterance: All right, the straws is a red herring.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.utterance: What it will do in terms of reducing our standard of living is - - Andrew Yang is being frank and honest with the American people. We're getting rid of private car ownership. That's what it's going to take. And we're going to have to modify people's diets. And if you took the time, Juan, to read Bernie Sanders' green new deal you would know exactly what he's up to --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yeah, then I'd run. I'd run out the studio. I'll be so scared, Dagen.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: By the way. By the way --

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.utterance: Can I just say something really quickly?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.utterance: He wants to ban fracking. How in the hell are we going to have natural gas to power the power plants to basically charge the electric cars? How is that going to happen?

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.utterance: They were protesting in India today, which I was glad to hear. Because that is a place that does not have emissions race that they have in the 1980's like we do here. And China would be nice. So I'd love to see this kind of protest happening in China.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I would listen to these activists if they were honest about what is clean fuel, and we know that it's nuclear. And more people, I think, I've read this, die from putting up solar panels than from actually nuclear power accidents.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Oh, wow.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You can quote somebody else. But that's -- I read that. I got that from John Stossel. John Stossel. The great John Stossel.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: All right. The liberal media running wild again, hyping an allege whistle blower complain against President Trump without knowing all the details, of course. The president fires back next on THE FIVE.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: I mean, this is incredibly high stakes for everybody involved at this point.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: This is truly uncharted territory.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: I feel like we're watching Vladimir Putin's best fantasy play out in real time.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: This is not only impeachable, it's not only wrong. It could well be a crime. And if it's not a crime, I don't know what the hell is.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: A new media firestorm out of Washington. A whistleblower reportedly says the president made a promise to a foreign leader that was concerning. And the Wall Street Journal reporting today, President Trump pressured the president of Ukraine about 8 times to investigate Joe Biden's son. The journal also reporting the source doesn't believe Trump offered any quid pro quo for that cooperation. But Democrats are demanding more information. And President Trump, he's firing back.

utterances.speaker: DONALD TRUMP, PRESIDENT
utterances.utterance: It's a partisan whistle blower. It's just another political hack job. It doesn't matter what I discuss. But I will say this, somebody ought to look into Joe Biden's statement because it was disgraceful. You had a very bad week, and this will be better than all of them. This is another one.

utterances.speaker: TRUMP
utterances.utterance: So keep playing it up because you're going to look really bad when it falls. You're not --

utterances.speaker: TRUMP
utterances.utterance: I guess I'm about 22 and 0, and I'll keep it that way.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Joe Biden just responding, he said President Trump's claim have no credibility. Jesse, let me go to you because the president said this is a political hack job, but what you can see is that, in fact, the inspector general of the director of national intelligence felt that he was obligated to pass this information to Congress, then, of course, they went to a lawyer who went to the Justice Department. The Justice Department said, oh, we're not sure this is urgent. But this wasn't a leak. It wasn't done irresponsibly. It went through appropriate channels. And now people are raising real concerns that there was a quid pro-quo.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: So the coup is going through appropriate channels now, Juan? Is that what we're talking about? I think this is going to be another bombshell that's gonna wind up in the garbage heap. But let me just break it down for you. I'll explain how the whole thing starts, OK?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: OK.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: So, this is a time when Joe Biden's son gets this no-show sweetheart deal job at a Ukrainian company that was backed by Vladimir Putin, right? So, this is at a time when Obama-Biden tried to peel away Ukraine from Russia. So all of a sudden this whole company falls apart because it's corrupt and they start being investigated by the Ukrainians. Joe Biden goes over there and tells Ukrainians fire the guy investigating my son's company or else you're not getting your billion-dollar loan. And you know what they do? They fire the guy investigating his son and they get the billion-dollar loan. And then a year later, the Ukrainians pass all the Manafort dirt to the Democrat National Committee, gets Manafort fired, and help starts up the whole Russia collusion thing. So now, Trump is being accused of being a colluder and being a corrupt. And he's says, wait a second, why am I being accused of this? Hey, Ukrainians, can you look into this sketchy little deal here? That's -- he had complete latitude as a commander-in-chief to ask a foreign country to investigate some corruption. We do it with Chinese. We do it to Mexicans all the time. And for some snake who I don't even trust to blow the whistle is just insurance policy 2.0. This president has to deal with this stuff constantly. It's going to fall apart again. And everything he's being accused of is the exact same thing Hillary and Biden were guilty of.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I would just say quickly that this has been looked at by major news organizations --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Kind of like the Russia hoax, right, Juan?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Excuse me. And they've all said, in fact, that Joe Biden's son and his whole business had collapsed more than a year before Joe Biden ever had anything to say to the Ukrainians. Now --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: No, no, no. He was still there at the time when Biden went over there --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, was not.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: -- and said he should not look into it.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Absolutely not.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: He took the money and ran then, Juan. Either way, he was still on the hook for an investigation.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I'm sure the president is pleased with your presentation. You can stop now.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Not about the president. It's about the truth, Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I think that -- if I was to get to the most powerful part of this allegation it would be that the president was extorting a foreign government for -- I think it was $250 million in defense aid in exchange for going after a political opponent, Joe Biden.

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.utterance: Except that the latest report we have doesn't say that. The quid pro quo part of this equation is one of the most important parts of this story. And the Wall Street Journal story tonight says that -- according to their finding there was no quid pro quo. That the president asked, they said 8 times, you really -- and can't you see him, saying 8 times. You really ought to look into this. You really ought to look into this.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Totally.

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.utterance: Did you hear me? You really ought to look into this Biden story because -- for the reasons I think that Jesse points out, he sees it as going all the way back to the beginning of this Russia probe to some extent. But the fact -- according to this report, at least, and I just want to caution everybody because we've been getting new information of this every several hours. So this is where it stands right now. According to the latest journal reporting, there was nothing offered in return for that. So that's important. And when you look back at Joe Biden's situation and you look at what he actually said. When you go back and look at the appearance that he made at the counsel of foreign relations, he's boasting about the fact that he did have a quid pro quo.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yeah, it's on tape.

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.utterance: He said I told them there is no way you're getting that billion-dollar loan guarantee unless you fire this guy. Now, he's -- and he was boasting about it. You know, I told them, tit for tat, right? It's the way it's going to be. You're not getting what you want unless you give me what I want. So that's a pretty clear quid pro quo and that's on tape, and that's Joe Biden talking about his situation himself.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: So, Greg, what we have here is a situation where Rudy Giuliani, last night, he says, well, no, I never asked the Ukrainians to do anything when I went over there. And then like 20 seconds later he said, well, yeah, of course I did.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah. He was actually -- that's how lawyers talk. He said that's -- I wasn't talking about that. I was talking about something related to that. And so it's just -- I mean, you can have that. It doesn't mean anything to me. I find it interesting that Trump is the only person the media approves of in terms of being investigated, right? You can't investigate Joe Biden. And if the media is going to ignore Joe Biden, then how dare you suggest it, right? And the fact is, it is so Trump to be saying, you should check this guy out -- because he does that about everything. He's always posing questions, why can't you do this? Why can't I fire this person? I'm not getting suckered into this story.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Every damn bombshell becomes a dud. If I reacted to every single story which the media's hair is on fire, I would need complete sedation. It's three-step story break to the media runs in front of it. They do. They act like it's the biggest thing in the world. And then when it's not, they all shrink away and find something else. It's a hysteria hamster wheel. They just hop on it and it fizzles. It's a business model predicated on apocalyptic fervor. And I ain't going to buy into it. And you know what sucks, Juan? When real things happens no one believes it anymore. No one believes it. This could be real, but no one is going to believe it. How can you believe the media on anything anymore when they completely exaggerate everything. Biden -- Biden doesn't want this story going anywhere near him either, because this is just going to put him in -- this is going to drag him into it.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: All right. So, Dagen, you know, so they're not allowing the Senate or the House to look at this whistle blower information. I'm thinking to myself if, in fact --

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.utterance: Today, in this hour, they're not --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Hang on. Not so far. So I'm thinking to myself, if the president's right, if there's nothing to this, why don't they want the Congress to see it?

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.utterance: I expect in the coming days you're going to get a transcript of this phone call because this whistleblower is not the only person who was probably on the call or had access to the transcript. And it will be clear as day exactly what was said. That's how you clear up anything that's going on because hamster wheels, Greg, make me nauseated. And who are you going to listen to? Adam Schiff who goes from zero to impeachment in a sneeze. A man who essentially lied to the American people about collusion for more than two years. Who are you going to believe?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I like hamsters, animals are great. President Trump mocks Bill de Blasio after the New York mayor drops his bid for the White House. Charles Barkley sounding off on Democrats and Beto O'Rourke's campaign, literally, getting stuck spinning in circles, another hamster for us, all in our 2020 political roundup straight ahead on “The Five.”

utterances.utterance: All right, time now for our 2020 round up. utterances.speaker: TRUMP
utterances.utterance: I see that our part-time mayor will be now going back to New York so they'll be able to work a little-bit harder. But he dropped out of the presidential race a little while ago. Too bad, he had tremendous potential. He only had one real asset. You know what it was? Height. Other than that he had nothing going.

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.utterance: So he's right about the work schedule. I think in May or June he worked about 7 hours, I believe. Over the course of that he takes his SUV to Brooklyn because he likes to go to his old gym all the time, and then he talk about climate change, but it didn't work. But he's going to come back and fix New York now.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You know, I think the big truth is that his absence wasn't missed. If anything, traffic moved better when he's not here. And the lesson is, being mayor of New York City is way easier than it looks if this dope can phone it in. Think about it. You've got a huge tax base. You have a bottomless supply of tourist dollars. You have a superior police and fire department. The mayor should just leave town permanently. We'll be fine.

utterances.utterance: I just like the fact that in couple of years Trump is still going to be president, he won't be mayor anymore. That is sweet justice. And one of the things that really, really don't appreciate this president for, Juan, is he really knows how to kick people when they're down. I mean, that is something we all need to reflect upon and I just love it.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, I agree. You know what?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You know what?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: A high five.

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.utterance: It's an art form, right?

utterances.utterance: I must say, on that score, Jesse's right. But I do think that says more about Trump that he's going to kick this guy when he's down than it says about the mayor.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: He can go back to smoking pot and dropping groundhogs. That's all he's good for anyway.

utterances.utterance: Is that right?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.utterance: Trump didn't go back to -- what is it? Like, he doesn't go show up for work in the oval office before noon. More personal time. He and de Blasio can hang out.

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.utterance: Executive time.

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.utterance: Not really quick, I've got a long memory, so I appreciate. I'll wait years to kick you when you're down. I really appreciate that. By the way, he's living, breathing example, de Blasio is of how socialism fails. Fails those most in need. And the Democrats need him gone. They're going to have a problem trying to explain their ideas with him around.

utterances.utterance: So, up next, outspoken NBA legend Charles Barkley calling out Democrats for ignoring black voters. Listen to this.

utterances.utterance: We need to start holding you Democrats accountable --

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: BARKLEY
utterances.utterance: -- because the point -- they've been taking black people's vote, and they only talk to black people every four years. But when they get elected they do nothing in the four years in between.

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.utterance: I mean, it's true, wise words, Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, you heard what he said. I think he says --

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.utterance: And he blames Republicans as well, by the way.

utterances.utterance: Democrats take you for granted, Republicans ignore you. utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: So, what.

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.utterance: I think you know I mean--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: So, what would people say, he has been the best president, you could argue for minorities and for women and for teenagers in terms of jobs. Right. They've had the lowest - you're laughing Juan, but there has been - the numbers of some of the lowest in history.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Where did those numbers declines take place, under President Obama.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That's not true.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: It is true. The majority of the decline from the height that it was at during the recession took place under President Obama.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: OK. So, even if we give you that Juan, OK. Worst case scenario, he allowed the beautiful numbers to keep pouring in for blacks and Hispanics. How does a racist do that?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: What are you saying? Because the economy--

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I mean if he is this big bad racist guy, then like he would have just stopped all this.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: And racist also - racist do that all the time.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: So, if he was really that incompetent, the numbers would have gone up.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I don't think he pays - I mean clearly if you're looking at programs that are intended to help with issues like health care or housing, this guy has not been there.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: What about prison reform?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: No, I think the point was that Barkley says--

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: What did Clinton and Obama do?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I think he did a lot.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: OK.

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.utterance: Well, I'm just curious you know because the economy was on decline and I'm just wondering in terms of race relations.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, let me just say again I don't think what - I mean in fact this is the Far Left that wants to attack Obama and say, you felt you had to be President of all the people, so you couldn't be the black president. That's the Left's argument. The Right's argument is, hey, we had such a slow climb in terms of out of the recession, it should have been faster. And they blame Obama for that. But the fact is the economy kept growing under Obama.

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.utterance: But then you're saying that the measure is how the economy does and how many people are listed by it. And then by that comparison--

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: By that comparison--

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.utterance: Trump is a better President for African Americans.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, by that comparison, thank you, Obama.

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.utterance: I'm very confused.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Juan makes no sense.

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.utterance: All right. Next one up, finally Beto O'Rourke having more trouble on the campaign trail, this time with his minivan.

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.utterance: Dagen, our car expert.

utterances.speaker: MCDOWELL
utterances.utterance: It's staged clearly. I don't know that but again Beto is kind of like casting stones, trying to figure out what he's going to do after he eventually drops out of this presidential race. Maybe that's it. Maybe he's going to start a tow service with his wife's family's money.

utterances.utterance: They have to film - he has to film everything and that always tells me that.

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.utterance: Bizarre.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: This has always been his own personal kind of search for self- worth. It wasn't about running for president, he needs to find out who he is.

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.utterance: I'm going to go find myself.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Well, I mean who is he? Is he driving the kids off at a soccer practice? Why is he in a minivan? I mean shouldn't he be--

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I thought he was going on a camping trip.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes, but in a minivan?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Why not? What have you got against minivans? You just don't like small things.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Do I need to say it? People run ads on the show. We love you, minivan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You know what I think Martha, I think it's that guy Yang you were talking about, he doesn't like cars. I bet he sabotaged the car.

utterances.utterance: Why is he always videotaping himself doing like things like that. Right. Like why not videotape like it's really successful today and here's what I did. It's always like I'm at the dentist, my car is stuck. He doesn't give you as a voter, he doesn't give you--

utterances.utterance: This guy is going to take care of everything.

utterances.utterance: He is trying to appear to be normal when he is probably a stone cold freak.

utterances.utterance: That makes me like him more.

utterances.utterance: Yes. That's what I've been told.

utterances.utterance: I mean who say sesh.

utterances.utterance: Yes.
